article.description:
Jalen Rose scored 27 points and Tyson Chandler had a career-high 22 rebounds and 19 points as the Chicago Bulls
beat the Denver Nuggets 88-69 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Chandler shows more than promise against Denver
article.linkText: Chandler's career effort helps Bulls blast Nuggets
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- Tyson Chandler had something to prove to the Denver Nuggets. Chandler had a career-high 22 rebounds and 19 points and Jalen Rose scored 27 points as the Chicago Bulls beat the Nuggets 88-69 on Saturday night. In the Bulls' last game against Denver, Chandler had six points and five rebounds. On Saturday night, he had 14 rebounds and 11 points in the first half alone "I had a bad game in Denver before the All-Star break and I wanted to come out and have a good game,'' Chandler said. Rose hopes Chandler can complement him in the offense. "I tell him all the time that I just need half of that every night,'' Rose said. "He has emerged as one of our most consistent young players.'' Chicago snapped an eight-game losing streak, while Denver dropped to 3-23 on the road with its 11th loss in 13 games. Chicago has the NBA's worst road record at 2-27. Denver was just 12-of-38 from the floor in second half and struggled shooting against the Bulls zone defense. "They went into the zone and that helped them out a lot. We weren't able to hit shots and weren't able to execute the offense,'' said Vincent Yarbrough. Lonny Baxter added 13 points and eight rebounds for the Bulls. Juwan Howard had 18 points for Denver, and Yarbrough had 11. The Nuggets shot 29 percent in the third quarter and were outscored 23-2 during an 8:30 span. Denver finished the game at 38 percent and went 2-for-8 from three-point range.

Game notes
The game featured 39 turnovers. Denver had 20 and Chicago 19. ... Chicago's Jay Williams needed two stitches to close a cut above his left eye. ... Despite both teams having terrible seasons the game drew a capacity crowd of 22,145. ... Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik had about 40 family members and friends attending the game. Bzdelik is from the northwest suburbs of Chicago. ... Bulls coach Bill Cartwright said after the game that he does not think he's in jeopardy of being fired. "I'm not worried about anything,'' Cartwright said. "I'm very fortunate. I think I am in a unique situation. All I'm going to do is my job and my job is to get these guys better and put them in a situation where they can be successful and I believe we are doing that.''
